At the top, a series of tabs - "Themes", "Desktop", "Screen Saver", "Appearance", and "Settings" - allow navigation through different display customization options. 

The "Themes" tab, currently active, allows users to manage visual themes for their Windows XP environment. A dropdown menu labeled "Theme:" lets users select from available themes, with "Windows XP (Modified)" currently selected. 

Below the dropdown, "Save As..." and "Delete" buttons provide options to save a modified theme or delete an existing one. 

At the bottom of the window, standard "OK", "Cancel", and "Apply" buttons allow users to apply changes, discard them, or confirm and close the window.

The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window with the "Screen Saver" tab now active instead of the "Themes" tab. 

The dropdown menu labeled "Screen saver:" has "Windows XP" selected. Below, a text field labeled "Wait:" is visible, but its content is not clear. The rest of the elements within the window remain as described in the initial state.

The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window, but the active tab is now "Screen Saver" instead of "Themes".  The "Screen Saver" dropdown menu shows "Windows XP" is selected. 

The previously described "Save As..." and "Delete" buttons are no longer present. Instead, there are "Settings" and "Preview" buttons next to the "Screen Saver" dropdown menu. Additionally, a "Power..." button is now visible at the bottom of the window, below the text "To adjust monitor power settings and save energy, click Power."

The screenshot shows the "Display Properties" window in Windows XP, specifically the "Screen Saver" tab. 

The active window displays the following elements:

- **Screen Saver** dropdown menu: Currently displaying "Windows XP", this menu allows users to choose from a list of available screen savers.
- **Wait:** field: This field, alongside the adjacent "minutes" label, allows users to specify the duration of inactivity before the chosen screen saver activates. It currently shows "10".
- **On resume, password protect** checkbox: This option, when checked, enables password protection upon returning from the chosen screen saver. Currently, the box is unchecked.
- **Settings** button: This button, currently inactive (greyed out), would allow users to adjust settings specific to the chosen screen saver.
- **Preview** button: This button allows users to preview the currently selected screen saver.
- **Monitor power** section: This section provides information and options related to the monitor's power settings.
- **Power...** button: This button opens the "Power Options Properties" window, granting access to advanced power management settings.
- **OK** button: Clicking this button applies any changes made within the "Display Properties" window and closes the window.
- **Cancel** button: Clicking this button discards any changes made within the "Display Properties" window and closes the window.
- **Apply** button: Clicking this button applies any changes made within the "Display Properties" window without closing it.

The screenshot shows two open windows: "Display Properties" and "Power Options Properties". 

The **"Power Options Properties"** window is in focus and contains the following:

* **"Power Schemes" tab:** This tab is currently selected and allows the user to manage power schemes.
* **"Home/Office Desk" power scheme:** This is the currently active power scheme, indicated by the selection in the dropdown menu.
* **"Settings for Home/Office Desk power scheme" section:** This section displays the configurable power settings for the selected scheme.
* **"Turn off hard disks" option:** This specific setting is set to "Never" in the dropdown menu. This determines when the hard disks will be powered down during inactivity. 
* **"OK" button:** Clicking this button will apply the current power scheme settings and close the window. 
* **"Cancel" button:** This button will discard any changes made to the power scheme settings and close the window.
* **"Apply" button:** This button will apply the current power scheme settings without closing the window.

In the background, the **"Display Properties"** window shows the "Screen Saver" tab open, but the specific settings within this tab are not the focus of this particular step.
